Bombarding in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of President Barack Obama's main assets.
It seems today, however, that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After stating in March last year that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama will lose face if he does not react forcefully to the murder, attributed to the Syrian regime, of more than 1000 civilians using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why on earth did Obama get himself entangled with such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
The U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to describe the use of gas as "moral obscenity."
But torturing children, precursors of the civil war two years ago, is no less reprehensible.
And is it morally more obscene to kill civilians with chemical products than to bomb them, shoot them, or allow them to die of starvation?
It is commonly admitted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Massive weapons of destruction, particularly nuclear bombs, certainly cause more damage and much faster than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing around 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb in Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo with incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to kill them in mass graves?
The viewpoint, defended notably by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, is that a swift punitive action could convince Syrian President Bashar al-Assad to give up on using chemical weapons and revert to "more commonplace means for massacring his people."
In my opinion, it makes no sense.
The question is surely that of the massacre, not the methods used.
In all cases, moral indignation, justified as it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese people in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds – with the support of the United States.
Is this therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons in fact constitutes a violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, to which it is a party.
Therefore, there are valid reasons to consider Assad as a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), incidentally established by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not easily defensible policy.
One could, however, suggest that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the primary Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn a blind eye when innocent people are massacred?
Tolerating a genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should one draw the line?
How many murders constitute a genocide?
Certainly! The French sentence "Des milliers?" translates to "Thousands?" in English.
The sentence "Des centaines de milliers?" in French translates to "Hundreds of thousands?" in English.
The sentence "Des millions?" in French translates to "Millions? " or " Millions?" in English. It seems like a simple question asking about millions or expressing surprise or disbelief regarding the mention of millions of something. Without more context, it's difficult to provide a more precise translation.
Does the number not count at all?
A genocide, after all, is a matter of intent; there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to reflect on before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through the use of sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
The translation of the given French sentence to English is:  "Responding to it implies asking: what is the best solution?"
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
As with the action of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a great power.
No one would consider launching missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or to enforce international laws and conventions pertaining to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
She is not a great power either.
But the civil war that rages there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, such as Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is absolutely not certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a more extensive conflict.
In fact, some proponents of American intervention – both neoconservatives and so-called "liberal hawks" – seem to want the opposite: they are calling for war with Iran.
And Obama probably established a link in his mind between the red line concerning Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as impulsively, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, can one expect from American strikes on Syrian targets when Obama has already indicated that they are not aimed at bringing down the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile will suffice to make the United States a direct participant in this war, triggering a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor doesn't seem particularly wise.
This viewpoint is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
This is the opinion of most Europeans.
And of a majority of Americans.
It might even be Obama's own view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the United States Congress the authorization to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relationships with Congress have not been easy.
But he needs it more than ever now to cover his tracks.
